title: doc improvements
Apply GraphTransformer EP specific rules to DNNL EP
body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
I'm working on improving DNNL execution provider through identifying operator fusions (conv-relu, matmul-add etc). 
I want to take advantage of onnxruntime's existing GraphTransformer infrastructure by adding DNNL ep as a compatible ep to certain fusion rules.
However, I found out that the fusion rule cannot be applied to DNNL EP as graph transformer rules will see fused node(s) from DNNL EP.
For example, say the graph consists of conv-relu-conv-relu, the DNNL EP will claim all 4 nodes in getcapability. When the ConvActivation fusion rule sees the graph later, it becomes a single fused node and the rule will not recurse into the fused node's function body.  

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using):
commit hash: d5922c594
Win10

**Describe the solution you'd like**
A clear and concise description of what you want to happen.
I want the GraphTransformer to be applied to DNNL EP when DNNL EP string is added as compatible eps to rules in onnxruntime\core\optimizer\graph_transformer_utils.cc

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
A clear and concise description of any alternative solutions or features you've considered.
It's possible to implement operator fusion infrastructure and rules in DNNL EP but it might be redundant (many fusions overlap with existing rules) and I believe it would be better to take advantage of the already existing GraphTransformer

**Additional context**
Add any other context or screenshots about the feature request here.

title: ms_experimental DFT feedback
body:
I have recently been using the DFT operator which is built with the `ms_experimental` flag and had some feedback and questions regarding the roadmap.

1. **Performance**: For input sizes which are power of 2 DFT dispatches to `fft_radix2`, [else it falls back to](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/contrib_ops/cpu/signal/dft.cc#L278-L281) `dft_naive` (which is incredibly slow). At a high level I understand why it is importance to have a power of 2 input for performance, but `torch.fft.ftt` is robust to other sizes and does not exhibit these same performance cliffs, so I was wondering if the onnxruntime implementation is able to be modified in the same way?
2. **Experimental status**: Are there plans to integrate these operators into the standard opset to avoid the need for the custom build flag in the future? There is an [open PR](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2625) to provide support for FFT as native ONNX operator, which could help fast-track this?
3. **EP alignment**: The ms_experimental op currently only supports the CPU execution provider, however there is a different fft implementation for CUDA in  `contrib_ops/cuda/math/fft_ops.h`, which has a different function signature and domain, are there any plans to align these so that a single model could access both operators, just by switching out the EP?

title: Optimize CUDA Kernel for 3D and 4D Transpose
body:
Optimized 4D transpose CUDA kernels so that it can take all permutations, most shapes. 
3D Trasnpose will be treated as 4D Transpose with the leading dimension being 0. 

Transpose120 can be treated as 2D transpose by coalescing the first two dimension. 2D Transpose will be handled by optimized TransposeWithCublas kernel. 

Transpose102 can be treated as specials case of Trasnpose0213 with first dimension being 1. This will handled by optimized Transpose4DParallelizeMultipleElementsPerThreadInInnermostDim kernel.

**Description**: 

Disable some graph optimizers that having negative impact on transformers optimization.

Current offline transformers optimization has two passes: one pass is to use OnnxRuntime to run graph optimization, and second pass is to use fusion in Python. In the second pass, we will use symbolic shape inference. 

Currently, there are two issues caused by first pass:
(1) Some contrib ops are not supported by symbolic shape inference. That could block the optimization in the second pass.
(2) Some fusion will change the graph, which will impact fusion in Python since those graph changes might impact fusion.

If we didn't set enable_onnx_checker=False to torch.onnx.export(), it reports this error

RuntimeError: No Op registered for CylinderQuery with domain_version of 13

If we set enable_onnx_checker=False to torch.onnx.export(), it reports this Warning

Warning: Unsupported operator CylinderQuery. No schema registered for this operator.

```python
class CylinderQuery(Function):
    @staticmethod
    def forward(ctx, radius, hmin, hmax, nsample, xyz, new_xyz, rot):
        # type: (Any, float, float, float, int, torch.Tensor, torch.Tensor, torch.Tensor) -> torch.Tensor
        r"""

        Parameters
        ----------
        radius : float
            radius of the cylinders
        hmin, hmax : float
            endpoints of cylinder height in x-rotation axis
        nsample : int
            maximum number of features in the cylinders
        xyz : torch.Tensor
            (B, N, 3) xyz coordinates of the features
        new_xyz : torch.Tensor
            (B, npoint, 3) centers of the cylinder query
        rot: torch.Tensor
            (B, npoint, 9) flatten rotation matrices from
                           cylinder frame to world frame

        Returns
        -------
        torch.Tensor
            (B, npoint, nsample) tensor with the indicies of the features that form the query balls
        """
        return _ext.cylinder_query(new_xyz, xyz, rot, radius, hmin, hmax, nsample)

    @staticmethod
    def backward(ctx, a=None):
        return None, None, None, None, None, None, None

    @staticmethod
    def symbolic(g: torch._C.Graph, radius, hmin, hmax, nsample, xyz, new_xyz, rot):
        return g.op("CylinderQuery", new_xyz, xyz, rot, radius_f=radius, hmin_f=hmin, hmax_f=hmax, nsample_i=nsample)


cylinder_query = CylinderQuery.apply
```

**Description**: 

Test a new form of LayerNorm (formula 1):
```
    def layer_norm(x ,weight, bias):

        y = x - u

        z = y / torch.sqrt(s + self.epsilon)
```

The result of `onnx::Xor(x, False)` is inconsistent between `x` having only 1 element, and more than 1 elements.

```
ort: [array([ True, False])]
torch: tensor([ True, False])

Testing logical_xor ([True], False):
ort: [array([False])]
torch: tensor([True])
```

```python
import onnxruntime as ort
import numpy as np
import torch

class M(torch.nn.Module):

x = torch.tensor([True, False])
```

title: Readily available Python wheels for ARM?

Currently, [PyPI](https://pypi.org/project/onnxruntime/#files) does not support `armv7l` platform for wheels. In response to this, [piwheels](https://www.piwheels.org/) was added to Raspberry Pi OS to offer pre-compiled builds of Python modules. piwheels builds from source in PyPI, which is not available for onnxruntime, and so there is still no widely-accepted place to get a Raspberry Pi-compatible wheel for onnxruntime.

I filed this issue at piwheels: https://github.com/piwheels/packages/issues/202

Is there any way that this can be resolved by providing source to PyPI, or providing ARM wheels in a separate Python repository?
